Two inmates of the Nigerian Correctional Services (NCS) Sapele, Delta State, have escaped from the centre in a jail break, just as five other inmates, State Comptroller sustained various degrees of injuries. The incident which happened on Tuesday evening, LEADERSHIP gathered that the Comptroller, Delta State Correctional Service, Ovie Friday and one other officer were also injured in the melee that ensued in the second aborted jail break attempt within two days. It was gathered that the two escapees, who were yet to be identified, scaled the high wall of the prison through the women section in the early hours of Wednesday, with tables laid to aid their escape, before security could be mobilized. On Monday, it was learnt the inmates had staged a violent protest, burning offices and properties of the centre over unfounded belief that the Federal Government approved the release of 25 members of them in the COVID19 amnesty, while the authority released only three. “The protest lingered till late at night and several attempts by the State Comptroller, Ovie Friday Ezesobor, to pacify them proved abortive. The inmates reportedly attacked the officials at night when some of them took steps to escape but were held, when two had succeeded. The Delta State Police Public Relations Officer, Onome Onowakpoyeya, DSP, confirmed the escape of the two inmates, adding that the Comptroller and one other officer were wounded. She said the five inmates that were injured by security agents were receiving treatments, stressing that normalcy had returned to the prison.